Name: Oats St & Orrong Rd, Carlisle South
Description: No opportunity to turn right onto Orrong Rd coming from Oats St Belmont direction
Location: {"Sector": "", "PlaceName": "", "Territory": "", "Neighborhood": "Carlisle South", "CountryCode": "AUS", "District": "", "City": "Perth", "Region": "Western Australia", "Address": "Oats St & Orrong Rd", "AddNum": "", "ShortLabel": "Oats St & Orrong Rd", "Subregion": "", "LongLabel": "Oats St & Orrong Rd, Carlisle South", "PostalExt": "", "Match_addr": "Oats St & Orrong Rd, Carlisle South, Western Australia, 6101", "Postal": "6101", "Type": "", "Addr_type": "StreetInt", "Block": "", "MetroArea": ""}
Comment 2: Dione: No arrow to turn right from Oats Street onto Orong Road towards the city. Very busy intersection with no safe nor efficient alternative near by. High traffic area which needs to be completely redesigned to cope with increase in population on the Belmont city side. Orong road is very busy and this intersection slows that down. It�۪s also a bus route and frequently used br cyclists.
Comment 4: Julia: There is no right turn arrow from Oats Street, Kewdale into Orrong Road, only a right turn arrow in the opposite direction from Oats Street, Carlisle into Orrong Road.  A lot of traffic turning into Orrong Road has to wait for the amber light and often traffic turns on the red light.  A fixed camera is needed as well as a green arrow from Oats Street, Kewdale into Orrong Road.
Comment 5: Julia: Only one green arrow, Oats Street Carlisle right into Orrong Road. No green arrow Oats Street Kewdale right into Orrong Road. ALL traffic trying to turn right into Orrong Road ends up having to turn on the amber light and often on the red light. Fixed cameras are also needed. The right turn arrow from Orrong into Oats also need to be programmed so that at quiet times the red arrow switches off. At present it stays red late at night and on weekends when traffic is lighter.
Comment 6: Volume of traffic and intersections get bottle necked

Name: 4, Kewdale
Description: WA drivers do not obey road rules! They constantly cross un-broken lines. I work at Toll Express and ride a motorcycle to work then drive a truck all day. I pass through this on ramp more than once a day. The on ramp is 100 k/hr and there is more than one car, 4x4, truck or anybody crossing that un-broken line. I have had on   more than one occasion where a driver has crossed over and cut me off whilst riding my bike to work.

Name: 3, Kewdale
Risk Second: Vehicles travel over the speed limit
Description: Vehicles constantly running the lights, should be an off ramp from Roe Hwy South from the left NOT a right turn from traffic lights across Roe Hwy on to Tonkin Hwy North. Poor road design for heavy vehicles with not enough time for trucks to pull away from the Tonkin Hwy South off ramp onto Roe Hwy North often they're caught in the middle of the inspection when the lights change.
Comment 1: Frances: When turning left onto Roe off Tonkin traffic is coming fast over crest to the right and much care is required. There will be a fatal accident .
Comment 3: Peter: As you travel East along the Roe Hwy, with the intention of turning left to travel North along the Tonkin, there is only 1, short-ish, narrow filter lane to accommodate this! There are often tailbacks of traffic back to the Welshpool Road overpass, and, far too many vehicles speed along this section and cross several lanes at the last minute to get onto the Tonkin. Very dangerous intersection!! I would suggest a major Police-blitz of this intersection!!
Comment 5: Todd: idiots constantly running red lights in both directions , the safety of those turning right onto roe from the exit here is of massive concern as they will be hit in drivers side of vehicle.    i see it all to frequently here in drive to work , the boneheads running late taking risks accelerating through amber & red.  A flash for cash redlight  camera may assit.
Comment 6: Andrew: 1. There are no flashing amber lights warning that the traffic lights are about to change when heading South. 2. When approaching the traffic lights the lights on both sides of the road can obscured from view by trucks in the left lane and the right turning pocket. Because there are no amber flashing lights sometimes you are not aware that the lights are amber or red. SOLUTION: Amber flashing lights and/or high set traffic lights positioned on a boom over the lanes.

Name: 3, Kewdale
Main Risk: Poor road markings or no edge-lines
Risk Second: Vehicles travel over the speed limit
Description: The major left hand turn on to Tonkin Highway  from Roe Highway is very poorly lane marked.

Name: 3, Kewdale
Description: Poor design with a single lane from one major hwy to another,  causes long tail backs, people become inpatient and push in at last minute whilst travelling at high speed.  Very poor design due to this being a major route for trucks, including B doubles.  Accidents there more than once a week.
